\par What is the situation in countries of the South regarding \lquote fair use\rquote  and \lquote fair dealing\rquote  provisions? There is no single pattern. While some countries do have \lquote fair dealing\rquote  provisions that are basically similar }{
\insrsid7217036 to}{\insrsid7603589  those in the developed world, a number of countries do not have any statutory provisions that expressly permit \lquote fair dealing\rquote  (or \lquote fair use.\rquote 
) The reason? Until quite recently, the copyright statutes in numbers of countries across Africa and Asia were essentially colonial transplants drafted by Europeans or their colonial underlings. Such statutes were often carbon copies o
f those that existed in the homeland of their then (or previous) colonial master, whether England or France or Spain. If such statutes supposedly \lquote worked\rquote 
 in England, then they were considered equally valid in countries such as Kenya, even though the conditions were radically different. Yet, in some African and Asian statutes, the \lquote fair dealing\rquote 
 clauses were, curiously, omitted. (Or perhaps not so curiously, as \lquote fair dealing\rquote  would at least have given some minimal rights to users when accessing works which,
 in most cases, would have been owned by publishers and other companies based in Europe.) Significantly, the leading global copyright agreement, the Berne Convention, does }{\i\insrsid7603589 not}{\insrsid7603589 
 require that members draft domestic copyright laws which mandate \lquote fair dealing\rquote  (or \lquote fair use\rquote ) provisions. In an era when the call to \lquote harmonise copyright laws\rquote 
 is growing increasingly shrill and when the rights of owners are becoming strengthened, protected, enforced -and more and more harmonised \endash  through international agreements such as the WIPO Copyright Treaty 1996, the call for \lquote 
harmonising users\rquote  rights\rquote  across the globe is seldom heard, let alone acted upon. 
\par 
\par So a call for the creation of \lquote fair dealing\rquote  (or \lquote fair use\rquote ) laws in every country in the world is certainly a demand worth supporting. And the best or broadest users\rquote 
 rights established anywhere in the world should become the global harmonised standard. Such provisions are particularly needed in the South where libraries are generally funded at much lower levels, where a
ccess to printed works is more tenuous and where the needs are especially pressing. Yet, at the same time \endash  }{\i\insrsid7603589 and this point cannot be made strongly enough \endash  }{\insrsid7603589 the transplanting of Northern \lquote 
fair dealing\rquote  (or \lquote fair use\rquote ) laws and standards to the South is }{\i\insrsid7603589 not}{\insrsid7603589  
the essential or principle solution to the information and knowledge needs, especially technical knowledge needs, of countries of the South and both their students and their teachers. 
\par 
\par Organisations which advocate the transplanting of US \lquote fair use\rquote  standards as the main access solution simply do not appreciate the \lquote on the ground\rquote 
 situation in the South. Looking across the full spectrum of the education field provides numerous instances of where a \lquote fair dealing\rquote /\rquote fair use\rquote  approach simply does not fit the bill. Four brief examples should suffice here: 

